ptions":["Increased stroke volume and increased end-diastolic volume","Increased stroke volume and increased end-systolic volume","Decreased stroke volume and increased end-diastolic volume","Decreased stroke volume and increased end-systolic volume","Decreased stroke volume and decreased end-systolic volume"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen the afterload of the heart increases, it leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased stroke volume and increased end-systolic volume\u003C/strong\u003E. Afterload is the pressure against which the ventricle must contract to eject blood. An increase in afterload makes it more difficult for the ventricle to empty, resulting in:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDecreased stroke volume: Less blood is ejected from the ventricle during each contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreased end-systolic volume: More blood remains in the ventricle at the end of systole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Increased afterload leads to decreased stroke volume and increased end-systolic volume.","Afterload is the pressure against which the ventricle must contract to eject blood."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kaplan, J.A. Kaplan\u0027s Essentials of Cardiac Anesthesia. 2018. 2nd edition. Elsevier. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1016/C2012-0-06151-0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43447"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43447"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-1